0":"1430–1490","1430–1480":"1430–1480","1467–1491":"1467–1491","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1490":"1490","Birmingham, Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","England":"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Colin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish and Manx: shortened Anglicized from <b>Ó Coileáin</b>, compare   Cullen  , or in Man or west Ulster shortened from <b>Mac Coileáin</b>, compare   McQuillan   and   McCallion  . The genitival <i>-s</i> is a local addition to   Collin   and variants after the surname was Anglicized.","Americanized form of French   Colin   or   Collin   and also   Collette  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Alfredo, Francisco, Jesus, Ricardo, Alberto, Angel, Arturo, Eduardo, Esteban, Faustino.  French Alexandre, Andre, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Claude, Jean-Michel, Laurette, Lucien, Marcel, Patrice, Pierre.","French, Walloon, and Breton: from a French shortened pet form of the personal name   Nicolas   (see   Nicholas  ). This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","English: from the personal name <i>Colin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Col</i>, itself a pet form of   Nicholas  ."]},{"name":"Kolenc","meanings":["Slovenian:","topographic name derived from <i>koleno</i> ‘knee’.","nickname from the dialect plant name <i>kolenc</i> ‘yellow bedstraw (Galium verum)’ or ‘common nipplewort (Lapsana communis)’. Compare   Collins   3."]},{"name":"Callins","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Collings","meanings":["English: variant of   Collins   or   Colling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah Collins was born in 1430, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with William Colemare. She died in 1490, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1430–1480":"1430–1480","1467–1491":"1467–1491","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1490":"1490","Birmingham, Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","England":"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1430–1480":"1430–1480","1467–1491":"1467–1491","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1490":"1490","Birmingham, Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"